summary: Ugh, it’s all so ugly and messed-up.   Pros of the new “Keeping Characters Dead”-Policy in the comics (assuming it’s implemented...
body:
Ugh, it’s all so ugly and messed-up.  

Pros of the new “Keeping Characters Dead”-Policy in the comics (assuming it’s implemented at all): 

[1] Nobody else gets to touch Tony Stark besides RDJ. 

[2] It *should* mean that only the most meaningful death will be executed, and only when absolutely necessary (read: NOT at any & every opportunity). 

Cons of the new “Keeping Characters Dead”-Policy in the comics (assuming it’s implemented at all): 

[1] This came about at a really sh*te time and given that the MCU is allegedly now Earth-616 rather than 19999, it means our boy might be gone for good. 

[2] It *could* be interpreted that any death applied to a character could still be twisted for shock value, especially now that they’re going to be made permanent.  So we’ll not only have 1 bab thing but 2 bab thing. ب_ب 

[3] While my loyalties don’t often align with corporate interest, I’m really hoping the folks working this decision recognize that it significantly cuts the mileage they can get out of a character if Permanent Death Syndrome is applied to them.

But, we all know Tony Stark would rather die than apologi-

I’d say it’s more likely that after getting comfortable with Tony he might slip up and almost call him uncle Ben but only get out the first letter or so before he realized. It’d probably sound like he just said “uhh” and Tony wouldn’t even notice the slip. Wouldn’t even realize what Peter means to him.

A lot sadder of an option but it makes more sense

Sorry for the angst

title: Project Resurgence
body:
Howard Stark, in a last ditch effort to recreate Captain America, decides to literally recreate him.

He takes a sample of the Caps DNA and from it creates a child. As far as outsiders are aware, the child is his and Maria’s. As far as Maria and the Jarvises are aware, the child is Howard’s illegitimate son.

Unfortunately none of the Super Soldier Serum’s effects carried over aside from healing some of the health problems Rogers had before the serum. As a result, Howard labels the project a failure and sets the clone aside, focusing his efforts back on trying to track down the original.

…

Tony Stark is ten when he discovers a file hidden in his father’s lab that states he’s not a Stark at all.
